Oribital Optimize Method with ADAPT Ansatz¶

As we already know that Hartree-Fock oribital are not optimal, therefore Oribital Optimize method can further improve the accurancy of VQE result. This page will show the performance of OO-ADAPT VQE.
Linear $H_4$ molecule with distance=2.0 A
This page will show how OO method can improve the result and compared with traditional way , which is setting more strict converge threhsold for ADAPT VQE. Moreover, How can OO method

ADAPT VQE converge detail:

  1. if the operator's engergy gradient lower than threshold => STOP
  2. If there is circulation has been detected (like: 27,14,3,3 operator 3 repeated)=> STOP

qebadapt_low_threshold.run_solver()

plt.title('Simulation of Linear $H_4$ R(H-H)=2.0 ')

plt.ylabel('Energy Error ($E_{ADAPT}-E_{exact}$) [Hartree]')
plt.legend()
Out[122]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7f6f6aa82d10>
We can see from the Figure above, more stright converge threshold for ADAPT VQE, higher accuracy will reach, while higher cost will be made. However the Oribital Optimize Method can be even higher accuracy in this case.¶
Therefore, Oribital Optimization + ADAPT Ansatz is a good combination for NISQ devices. Because OO Method do not cost any real quantum hardware. ¶
In the end,we compared the hardware cost:¶
In [107]:
#compare cost 
#qebadapt_low_threshold's cnot number: 496
qebadapt_low_cnot_num = qebadapt_low_threshold.adapt_ansatz.decompose(reps=6).count_ops()['cx']
#qebadapt_high_threshold's cnot number: 884
qebadapt_high_cnot_num = qebadapt_high_threshold.adapt_ansatz.decompose(reps=6).count_ops()['cx']

plt.bar(['QEB-ADAPT 1e-3','QEB-ADAPT 1e-4'],[qebadapt_low_cnot_num,qebadapt_high_cnot_num],color=['orange','blue'])

plt.text('QEB-ADAPT 1e-4', qebadapt_high_cnot_num, str(qebadapt_high_cnot_num), ha='center', va='bottom')
